text:
Swisscom AG is Switzerland’s leading telecommunications and information technology company, with a notable presence in Italy through its subsidiary Fastweb. The company is headquartered in Ittigen, near Bern, and provides a comprehensive array of services, including mobile and fixed-line telephony, broadband internet, digital television, and various IT services. As of 2023, Swisscom employed approximately 19,729 full-time equivalents and reported revenues exceeding 11 billion CHF.

Swisscom traces its origins back to 1851 with the establishment of a state-run telegraph service in Switzerland, evolving into telephone communications and eventually the PTT (Post, Telegraph, and Telephone) in 1920. The telecommunications division was separated from postal services in 1997, creating Swisscom, which was partially privatized the following year.

A significant milestone in Swisscom's expansion was acquiring a majority stake in the Italian telecommunications company Fastweb in 2007. As of recent reports, Swisscom holds a strong position in the Swiss market with significant market shares in mobile communications (56%), broadband internet (51%), and digital television (37%). In Italy, Fastweb commands a 16% market share among private broadband customers and 29% among corporate clients.

Swisscom is recognized as one of Switzerland’s most innovative and sustainable companies, investing significantly in research and development to advance telecommunications technology. The company is involved in sustainability initiatives focused on reducing environmental impact and promoting energy efficiency.

In recent developments, Swisscom announced plans in March 2024 to merge Fastweb with Vodafone Italia to strengthen its position in the Italian market. The Swiss government holds a 51% controlling interest in Swisscom, underscoring its strategic importance to national infrastructure.

Swisscom faces competition from other telecommunications providers like Sunrise and UPC, yet it maintains a leading position in several market segments. The company launched its 5G network in April 2019, placing Switzerland among the first countries to adopt this technology.
